{
  "text": "The areca nut is the seed of the palm plant Areca catechu L. and is rich in alkaloids, including arecoline, arecaidine, guvacine, and guvacoline. Sundqvist et al. demonstrated that the aqueous extract and the above four alkaloids from the areca nut are highly cytotoxic and genotoxic to human cultured cells and have the potential to induce tumors [CITATION_1] . Additionally, several reports have shown the association of chewing areca nuts with the development of various disorders, such as cardiovascular disease [CITATION_2] , metabolic syndrome [CITATION_3] , and hypertension [CITATION_4] . In spite of these various harmful properties, the areca nut is still used in traditional Chinese medicine and in India. It was found to be a highly effective treatment for human taeniasis [CITATION_5] and increased memory and learning in a rat model [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
